The paper deals with natural language processing and machine learning techniques to extract commonsense knowledge from a large corpus. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the sub-category of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL). Additionally, the paper involves the use of machine learning algorithms, which suggests that it could also belong to the sub-categories of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG). The paper also involves information retrieval techniques to aggregate scores of entity pairs, which could place it in the sub-category of Information Retrieval (cs.IR). Finally, the paper deals with benchmark datasets for evaluation, which could place it in the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI).
